ğŸ¯ Overview

A function in PHP is a reusable block of code that performs a specific task.
Functions help make your code modular, readable, and maintainable.

ğŸ’¡ Why Use Functions?

ğŸ” Avoid repeating code

ğŸ§© Improve code structure

âš™ï¸ Make maintenance easier

ğŸš€ Reuse logic across projects

ğŸª¶ Simplify debugging and testing

âš™ï¸ Types of Functions

Built-in Functions â†’ Provided by PHP (e.g. strlen(), date(), strtoupper() etc.)

User-defined Functions â†’ Created by the programmer for custom tasks.

ğŸ§± Syntax
function functionName($parameter1, $parameter2, ...) {
    // Code to execute
    return $value; // Optional
}

ğŸ§© Example:
<?php
function greet() {
    echo "Hello, welcome to PHP functions!";
}

greet(); // Function call
?>

ğŸ§  Function with Parameters
<?php
function add($a, $b) {
    return $a + $b;
}

echo add(10, 5); // Output: 15
?>

âš¡ Default Parameter Values
<?php
function greet($name = "Guest") {
    echo "Hello, $name!";
}

greet();        // Output: Hello, Guest!
greet("Ravi");  // Output: Hello, Ravi!
?>

ğŸ” Returning Values
<?php
function square($n) {
    return $n * $n;
}

echo square(4); // Output: 16
?>

ğŸ§® Returning Multiple Values
<?php
function calculate($a, $b) {
    $sum = $a + $b;
    $diff = $a - $b;
    return array($sum, $diff);
}

list($sum, $diff) = calculate(10, 5);
echo "Sum: $sum, Difference: $diff";
?>

ğŸª„ Variable Function Names
<?php
function sayHello() {
    echo "Hello from dynamic function!";
}

$func = "sayHello";
$func(); // Calls sayHello()
?>

ğŸ”¤ Function Type Declarations (PHP 7+)
<?php
function multiply(float $a, float $b): float {
    return $a * $b;
}

echo multiply(3.5, 2); // Output: 7
?>

ğŸ”— Pass by Reference
<?php
function addTen(&$num) {
    $num += 10;
}

$value = 20;
addTen($value);
echo $value; // Output: 30
?>

ğŸ” Recursive Function
<?php
function factorial($n) {
    if ($n == 0) return 1;
    return $n * factorial($n - 1);
}

echo factorial(5); // Output: 120
?>

ğŸ•¶ï¸ Anonymous (Lambda) Function
<?php
$greet = function($name) {
    return "Hello, $name!";
};

echo $greet("Priya");
?>

ğŸ§­ Arrow Function (PHP 7.4+)
<?php
$multiply = fn($a, $b) => $a * $b;
echo $multiply(3, 4); // Output: 12
?>

ğŸ§© Variable Scope in PHP Functions
Scope Type	Description
Local	Declared inside a function; accessible only within it
Global	Declared outside; can be accessed inside using global
Static	Retains its value between function calls
Example:
<?php
function counter() {
    static $count = 0;
    $count++;
    echo $count . "<br>";
}

counter(); // 1
counter(); // 2
counter(); // 3
?>

ğŸŒ Using Global Variables
<?php
$siteName = "Pride Computers";

function showSite() {
    global $siteName;
    echo "Welcome to $siteName!";
}

showSite();
?>

ğŸ§© Example: Complete Program
<?php
function studentInfo($name, $course, $marks) {
    echo "Student Name: $name <br>";
    echo "Course: $course <br>";
    echo "Marks: $marks <br>";

    if ($marks >= 50) {
        echo "Result: Pass <br><br>";
    } else {
        echo "Result: Fail <br><br>";
    }
}

studentInfo("Ravi", "MS-CIT", 78);
studentInfo("Pooja", "Tally Prime", 45);
?>

ğŸ§­ Best Practices

âœ… Use meaningful names for functions
âœ… Keep functions short and focused
âœ… Use type declarations for clarity
âœ… Avoid global variables when possible
âœ… Use return for flexibility instead of echo

ğŸ§  Summary Table
Concept	Description	Example
Function Declaration	Create a reusable block	function test(){}
Parameters	Pass values	function add($a,$b){}
Return	Send back result	return $sum;
Default Values	Use fallback	function greet($n="Guest")
Recursive	Calls itself	factorial()
Anonymous	No name	$fn = function(){}
Arrow	Short syntax	fn($a)=>$a*2
